                    <span>I read this for my history of childhood course (I'm a history major) and this was a fascinating read into the life of a Jewish immigrant from Eastern Europe.  She learns to find her own happiness after watching her father arrange marriages for her three sisters to men they don't love.  After every chapter, I felt like going into the book and just screaming at Sara's pious, lazy Orthodox Jewish father who does nothing but study his Holy Torah.  This book should be required reading not just in colleges but in high schools, too.</span>
                  
              
